3. The `ban` command has two options: `member` (a required user parameter) and `reason` (an optional string parameter).
4. In the `execute` function, we retrieve the specified member and reason, then implement your ban logic (in this example, using `member.ban()`). Finally, we respond to the interaction with a message indicating the ban was successful.
5. We set up an event listener for the `ready` event to log a message when the bot is online.
6. Don't forget to replace `YOUR_DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN` with your actual Discord bot token.

